Sugary drinks and snacks were blamed for the fact that 27.9 per cent of five-year-olds have tooth decay
David Cheskin/PA
Chris Smyth Health Correspondent
Published at 12:01AM, September 20 2013
One in four children has tooth decay by the age of five, according to figures from Public Health England.
The figure rises to one in three in the North West while in Leicester more than half of five-year-olds have teeth that are decayed, missing or filled.
A survey of 134,000 children by Public Health England found that while children’s teeth are in better shape than they were five years ago, hundreds of thousands of youngsters still have bad teeth.
